## React State Management

### Decision Matrix
| Scope | Tool | When |
|-------|------|------|
| Component-local | `useState` | Form values, toggle, hover |
| Multi-component | `useState` + props | Sibling components |
| Feature-wide | `useContext` + `useReducer` | Auth, theme, modal state |
| App-wide client | Zustand or Jotai | Cross-feature shared state |
| Server state | TanStack Query or SWR | API data, caching, sync |
| Large complex app | Redux Toolkit | Complex update logic, DevTools |

### Server state: TanStack Query
```ts
// Cache, refetch, deduplicate — don't duplicate into Zustand
const { data: users, isLoading } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ['users'],
  queryFn: fetchUsers,
  staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 min
});

const mutation = useMutation({
  mutationFn: createUser,
  onSuccess: () => queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['users'] }),
});
```

### Zustand: app-wide client state
```ts
interface AuthStore {
  user: User | null;
  setUser: (user: User | null) => void;
  logout: () => void;
}

const useAuthStore = create<AuthStore>((set) => ({
  user: null,
  setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
  logout: () => set({ user: null }),
}));
```

### Anti-patterns
```ts
// WRONG: duplicating server state into Zustand
const useStore = create(() => ({ users: [], loading: false }));
// Then manually fetching and setting... just use TanStack Query

// WRONG: Redux for simple app state that Context handles fine
```

### Checklist
- [ ] Server data in TanStack Query (not duplicated in client store)
- [ ] No redundant computed state (derive, don't store)
- [ ] URL state for shareable filters/pagination
- [ ] Context not used for high-frequency updates (use Zustand)

## React Performance

### Profile before optimizing
```tsx
// React DevTools Profiler → find components with high render time
// Only optimize what's measured as slow
```

### When to use useMemo
```tsx
// CORRECT: expensive computation (filtering large list)
const filteredUsers = useMemo(
  () => users.filter(u => u.role === selectedRole),
  [users, selectedRole]
);

// WRONG: cheap operation — memo overhead > savings
const fullName = useMemo(
  () => `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`,
  [user.firstName, user.lastName]
);
// Just do: const fullName = `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`;
```

### When to use useCallback
```tsx
// CORRECT: function passed to React.memo child — stable ref prevents re-render
const handleSelect = useCallback(
  (id: string) => dispatch({ type: 'SELECT', id }),
  [dispatch]
);
return <ExpensiveList onSelect={handleSelect} />;

// WRONG: inline function that's never passed down
const handleClick = useCallback(() => setOpen(true), []);
// Just do: onClick={() => setOpen(true)}
```

### React.memo for expensive pure components
```tsx
const UserRow = React.memo(function UserRow({ user, onSelect }: UserRowProps) {
  return <tr onClick={() => onSelect(user.id)}><td>{user.name}</td></tr>;
});
// Only re-renders when user or onSelect ref changes
```

### Virtual lists for large data
```tsx
// Don't render 10,000 rows — virtualize
import { FixedSizeList } from 'react-window';
<FixedSizeList height={600} itemCount={users.length} itemSize={50}>
  {({ index, style }) => <UserRow style={style} user={users[index]} />}
</FixedSizeList>
```

### Checklist
- [ ] useMemo/useCallback added after profiling, not preemptively
- [ ] React.memo on expensive pure components only
- [ ] Lists > 100 items use virtualization
- [ ] React DevTools Profiler used before optimizing
- [ ] No premature memoization of cheap operations

